Anything that helps us function in society and makes our lives just a teensy tiny bit easier is an accomodation that should be welcomed. Because guess what? None of us will even live to see a post capitalist society. We need comfort and lives worth living NOW.

Yeah sure it sucks that this is what it takes. But guess what??? ADHD is a disability in a world that is not disability friendly. Would you tell a person who needs mobility accomodations "well without capitalism you wouldn't need that so you shouldn't use it?"

Dopamine deficiency is way more than "i can't focus". It's i can't do basic bodily functions without the adrenaline of a near disaster. It's i don't know where time (counted by the clock or by the sun) has gone. It's i promised to do stuff i forgot and now everyone is upset
Which takes me to 2) because if you truly have adhd, no medication will make you a hyperfocus machine. It will make you think damn i should go to the bathroom and you stand up and go
You know that thing that ADHD does where you blink and FIVE HOURS have gone and you have not moved from your bed? Yeah. Gone with Ritalin.

Because it is too late, and I too have been through the making of a Global South person. And no matter where I go, the gunshot and the wails of a mother without a son will ring in my ears the day I die. There is not a thing I would not do for my children to have silence.

Leaving is hard, but so is staying. And so what we ask - and especially us Latin Americans - is that you understand that staying here is also a fucking nightmare we can't wake up from, and that the least we deserve is a little bit of respect for our struggle.

It would have meant forgetfulness; that your pain would cause no harm in the world. That your blood would be shed for a company to destroy your homeland for profit. That wars would be waged over your unmarked grave.

It is extremely upsetting to see people discredit this profoundly traumatic experience. "I could have been raised in this beautiful place" means you would have been raised subjected to trauma beyond belief, and would do it with a smile on your face.

No land will know us this well. No food will fill us up as well. No embraces will be as warm. Nothing will ever compare to this place you were born in, but staying will get you killed; as brazilian Caetano Veloso says, "of fright, of bullet or of vice".

but also because we are so exhausted that sometimes leaving is easier on the mind. And it hurts us so to leave us behind, because the Global South experience is to live a nightmare in a place of dreams.

Whenever we from the Global South say "the experiences of the diaspora are very different from ours", is not because we want to disqualify the diaspora experiences. The diaspora happens because parents do not want their children to experience things like that

When they said "that's gunfight" I remembered a scene from my childhood: being woken at night with a mother's piercing wail, holding the body of her child with half a head blown off by a gunshot, cursing God for giving her a child only to take him away from her like that.

My case is a different one: I was raised in a humble family, where my Grandmother lived in a favela similar to that one in Rio, and I managed to enter an university that catapulted me into elite spaces. One foot in absolute poverty, one in absolute wealth.

For us, however, who are here, who live here, who breathe here, there is no reprieve from it. We live alongside absolute beauty and horrifying massacres every single day, and we do what we can not to think about it too much.

Rio de Janeiro is probably one of the most exotified places in the Global North. It's the center of the North's collective fantasy of a Global South willing and ripe for the taking, with a violence they are curious about because it does not affect them.

@AliCatWrites in brazil that is at least 40 types of illegal skljdflsdfkgh

17) this is the type of employment that is the most common, called "celetista". if you are a civil servant working in the public sector, you are "estatutário", which means you have all this + permanent stability, so you cannot be fired at will

16) on top of that, the companies and the union will agree on a "Collective Work Agreement", which will add bonuses, wage increases, career plans or other duties the company needs the employees to do. this has become laxer in later years (thanks, bolsonaro)
15) to be hired in a job, you have to show documentation that your children are in school and vaccinated. if you have a child with special needs you can lower your time without lowering your wage.
or just give you a "food ticket" that comes in a card and you spend it with food only. dad gets that and a "grocery ticket" which we use for groceries. again, not a right, but most employers do

14) bonus: this is not necessarily a right, but most companies have some sort of company healthcare system. this is mostly for comfort/ease/speed, since we have public health care. they will also offer transportation + food support and add it to the wage

13) in union law terms: union busting is a crime. a company  cannot interfere in an union under any circumstances. it is illegal to hire workers to replace workers on strike. union leaders have job stability, therefore cannot be fired

fair cause firing is because of a grave fault of the employee (stealing, fucking up the operation deliberately, misconduct). then you only get your proportional pay for the month. a mistake is not a fair cause warning. the employer needs a serious reason for this

12) firing at will and fair cause warning: employers can fire you at will, provided they pay: proportional days worked, proportional 13th wage, proportional pto + 1/3 of pto bonus, FGTS  + 40% of the total FGTS saved + 1 month worth of wage if they don't give you a 30days notice

11) INSS, or national institute of social security. Every month you will contribute a little for this fund. If you need to take more than 15 sick days consecutively the INSS will take over your payment. it's also where your retirement will come from

10) FGTS, or Severance Indemnity Fund. every month your employer will pay a little bit to a savings account in your name. if you get fired at will you can get this value, or if you want to make a downpayment for a house you can access it, but otherwise it's locked

but it is paid as compensation because it is illegal to do so
8) guaranteed 12 hour rest in-between shifts
9) no work sundays. if you work in an industry that requires sunday work your time off has to be on sunday at least once a month

6) thirteenth wage. in december you get twice your monthly pay. like a bonus, but if you don't get it, you can sue your employer for the skin of his back 
7) 2h overtime max. overtime hour is the full hour + 50% of the value. if you work even more than that is double the hour+

3) 120 days maternity leave, often pushed for 180
4) if you are pregnant/post-partum you have job stability, meaning you cannot be fired for any reason other than, idk, stealing fromt he company 
5) your sick days apply for your children too. so you can take children sick days

and i just realized i have this difficult task of looking at myself with grace, understanding the child i was trying to function in a neurotypical world and being punished for it, and loving this child i hated for so long because i thought she was the source of my problems

and so i internalized this. i was an unlikeable child. i cannot be like that anymore or i will simply be unlikeable and i will continue to be alone. i didn't expect to unpack all this trauma with the diagnosis but i've just had a difficult therapy session

i don't blame my parents because they were as woefully unprepared for it as they still were. but all of those things (and because i never had grade problems, i generally could go well without studying much or at all) were written off as "flaws", things that made me unlikeable

one thing that i didn't expect with my adhd diagnosis is looking at my childhoon/teenage years and seeing that all the things i thought made me a bad person (talking too much, restlessness, authority defiance, unable to finish schoolwork) were just signs no one listened

But this has never been about Americans. At no point LATAM activists considered the American experience and comfort in developing this tool. I know y'all are not ready to not be the center of the universe but like...... This ain't got nothing to do with you

All of this is rooted in LATAM struggle and activism. These are issues that stem from our concerns and that bleed on the American political landscape, which i unfortunately have to know about bc y'all might want to coup us again and i have to be ready

The use of the "x/e" is gender neutral, which accommodates different gender expressions and stops the masculine from being totalizing. This is important for a language that is not neutral. We're struggling to come with an equivalent to "they".

There is also the issue the plural is on the masculine. If I have 5 women in a room, i could say "Todas", but as soon as a man enters, I would have to say "todos". The masculine is the standard, and for a region riddled with gender violence, that is a heavy symbolism

"what do you mean gendered words" everything in Spanish/Portuguese is gendered. If I want to say my NB sibling is a dear, the "correct" way is to say querido (male) or querida (female). My sibling is Nb. I say "queride".

And i do not care who in your family came from LatAm, you don't get to police how we work and modify our language to suit our needs. If you're an American, either do your research or do get the fuck out
